# Memory Leaking in Rust with `Box::leak`

## What `Box::leak` Does

`Box::leak` converts a `Box<T>` into a `&'static mut T`, intentionally preventing the destructor from running and giving the value a `'static` lifetime.

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::sync::OnceLock;

// ============================================================
// Example 1: Static configuration loaded once at startup
// ============================================================

#[derive(Debug)]
struct AppConfig {
    database_url: String,
    max_connections: u32,
    feature_flags: HashMap<String, bool>,
}

impl AppConfig {
    fn load() -> Self {
        AppConfig {
            database_url: String::from("postgres://localhost/mydb"),
            max_connections: 10,
            feature_flags: HashMap::from([
                (String::from("dark_mode"), true),
                (String::from("beta_features"), false),
            ]),
        }
    }
}

impl Drop for AppConfig {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        // This will NEVER be called when we use Box::leak
        println!("AppConfig dropped (you won't see this with Box::leak)");
    }
}

/// Leak config once, get a &'static reference usable everywhere.
/// Appropriate because: lives for program duration, needed in many places,
/// and the OS reclaims memory on process exit anyway.
fn get_static_config() -> &'static AppConfig {
    static CONFIG: OnceLock<&'static AppConfig> = OnceLock::new();

    CONFIG.get_or_init(|| {
        let config = Box::new(AppConfig::load());
        Box::leak(config) // &'static AppConfig
    })
}

